## Installation

```bash
npm i @webtypen/webframez-core
```

For local development in this repository:

```bash
npm install
npm run build
npm run build:check
npm run dev
```

`npm run dev` starts `ts-node ./dev/app.ts` with `PORT=3210` according to `package.json`.

## Minimal Web Application

```ts
import { BaseKernelWeb, Request, Response, Route, WebApplication } from "@webtypen/webframez-core";

class Kernel extends BaseKernelWeb {
  static controller = {
    TestController: class {
      async index(req: Request, res: Response) {
        return res.send({ status: "ok" });
      }
    }
  };

  static middleware = {
    auth: async (next: Function, reject: Function, req: Request, res: Response) => {
      if (!req.headers.authorization) {
        return reject("Unauthorized");
      }
      next(true);
    }
  };
}

const app = new WebApplication();
app.boot({
  kernel: Kernel,
  port: 3000,
  basename: null,
  routesFunction: () => {
    Route.get("/", "TestController@index");
  }
});
```

## Boot Options

`WebApplication.boot(...)` accepts these common options:

- `kernel`: kernel class with controller and middleware registries.
- `port`: HTTP port, default `3000`.
- `basename`: optional route prefix applied by the router.
- `routesFunction`: function that registers routes through `Route`.
- `modules`: array of module provider classes.
- `config`: object registered into the global `Config` facade.
- `datatables`: table key to `Datatable` class map.
- `jobs`: queue job classes.
- `mode`: runtime mode passed to router and response.
- `onBoot`: callback called after the server starts.
- `errorHandler`: single handler or array of handlers for framework error events.

## TypeScript

The package builds with `tsc`. Published files are `dist`, `README.md` and `agents`.

## Routing

Use the `Route` facade to register routes:

```ts
Route.get("/", "HomeController@index");
Route.post("/login", "AuthController@login");
Route.put("/users/:id", "UserController@update");
Route.delete("/users/:id", "UserController@delete");
```

Inline handlers are supported when a controller is not needed:

```ts
Route.get("/health", (req: Request, res: Response) => {
  return res.send({ status: "ok" });
});
```

## Path Patterns

Supported route patterns include:

- Required parameters: `/:id`
- Optional parameters: `/:id?`
- Single wildcard: `/*`, available as `req.params.splat`
- Catch-all wildcard: `/**`, available as `req.params.wildcard`

Named route params are available on `req.params`.

## Route Groups

```ts
Route.group({ prefix: "/admin", middleware: ["auth"] }, () => {
  Route.get("/dashboard", "AdminController@dashboard");

  Route.group({ prefix: "/users" }, () => {
    Route.get("/:id", "AdminUserController@details");
  });
});
```

Group middleware and route middleware are merged and de-duplicated. Group domains and route domains are merged the same way.

## Domain Filters

Routes and groups can be restricted to domains:

```ts
Route.group({ domains: ["websites.simplebis.com", "*.local.dev"] }, () => {
  Route.get("/", "HomeController@index");
});

Route.get("/api/health", "HealthController@index", {
  domains: ["api.example.com"]
});
```

The router checks `x-forwarded-host`, `x-original-host` and `host`, normalizes ports and schemes, and supports wildcard domain segments. The matched hostname is available as `req.routeDomainMatch`; a wildcard capture is available as `req.routeDomainWildcard`.

## Middleware

Middleware is registered by key on the kernel and attached with route options or groups:

```ts
static middleware = {
  auth: async (next: Function, reject: Function, req: Request, res: Response) => {
    if (!req.headers.authorization) {
      return reject("Unauthorized");
    }
    next(true);
  }
};

Route.get("/me", "AccountController@me", { middleware: ["auth"] });
```

The middleware signature is `(next, reject, req, res)`. Rejecting middleware is converted into a framework error response.

## Request

`Request` exposes `method`, `url`, `pathname`, `headers`, `rawHeaders`, `body`, `bodyPlain`, `query`, `queryRaw`, `params`, `files`, `socket`, `message`, `routeDomainMatch`, `routeDomainWildcard` and `skipOptionsForward`.

## Response

Common helpers:

```ts
res.status(201);
res.header("X-Test", "1");
res.send({ status: "success" });
```

Additional helpers include `sendCsv(...)`, `download(...)`, `stream(...)`, `end()`, `registerEvent("after", fn)` and event handling through `handleEvents(...)`.

## Configuration

`Config` is a global facade. Boot options register each top-level config key:

```ts
app.boot({
  config: {
    database,
    queue,
    storage
  }
});
```

Use `Config.get("database.defaultConnection")` for dot-path reads and `Config.set("storage.defaultDisk", "public")` for updates.

## Database Drivers

Database access is driver-based:

```ts
DBDrivers.register("mongodb", MongoDBDriver);
```

A driver extends `BaseDBDriver` and can implement:

- `connect()` and `close(client)`.
- `handleQueryBuilder(client, queryBuilder)`.
- `execute(client, data, options)`.
- `objectId(val)`.
- `onModelSave(model, saveStatus)`.

`DBConnection` reads `Config.get("database")`, resolves the default connection, caches active driver/client pairs and delegates query execution to the driver.

## Models

Models extend `Model` and define at least `__table`. Optional fields include `__primaryKey`, `__connection`, `__hidden` and `__unmapped`.

```ts
class User extends Model {
  __table = "users";
  __hidden = ["password"];
}

const user = await User.where("email", "=", email).first();
```

Static model helpers include `objectId(...)`, `where(...)`, `orderBy(...)`, `first(...)`, `get(...)`, `paginate(...)` and `aggregate(...)`.

Instance helpers include `save()`, `update(...)`, `delete()`, `toArray()`, `getModelData()` and instance `objectId(...)`.

Relationships are available through decorators/functions: `hasOne`, `hasMany` and `hasManyArray`.

## QueryBuilder

`QueryBuilder` stores table, where conditions, sort, limit, offset and execution mode. It supports `where`, `orderBy`, `take`, `offset`, `get`, `first`, `paginate`, `count` and `delete`.

## Storage

Use the `Storage` facade instead of direct filesystem access for standard file operations:

```ts
const filepath = await Storage.disk("public").put(buffer, "exports/report.csv");
const file = await Storage.disk("public").file(filepath);
const exists = await file.exists();
```

Supported facade operations include `put`, `copy`, `move`, `delete`, `mkdir`, `isDir`, `isFile`, `file`, `readDir` and `upload`. The default built-in driver is `local`, configured through `storage.defaultDisk` and `storage.disks.<key>`.

## Datatables

Datatables are classes extending `Datatable`. They provide a MongoDB aggregation-based data API for frontend tables, including init metadata, filters, columns, pagination, sums, row hooks, exports and selectable bulk actions.

## Define A Table

```ts
import { Datatable, Request } from "@webtypen/webframez-core";

export class UsersTable extends Datatable {
  collection = "users";
  perPage = 25;

  columns = {
    name: { label: "Name" },
    email: { label: "E-Mail" }
  };

  filter = {
    name: { type: "text", mapping: "name", regex: true }
  };

  aggregation = async (req: Request) => {
    return [{ $sort: { created_at: -1 } }];
  };
}
```

`collection`, `aggregation`, `subAggregation`, `filter`, `columns` and `onPressLink` may be static values or functions receiving `Request`.

## Register Tables

```ts
app.boot({
  datatables: {
    users: UsersTable
  }
});
```

## Expose Endpoints

```ts
Route.post("/api/datatable", "DatatableController@restApi");
Route.post("/api/datatable/export", "DatatableController@tableExport");
```

`DatatableController@restApi` supports:

- init requests with `init_request`.
- paginated data responses.
- selectable functions via `apiFunction`.

`DatatableController@tableExport` uses the selected table's `exports` definition and returns base64 export data.

## Filtering

The filter system supports common operators and special values such as `==null`, `!=null`, `==[...]`, `!=[...]`, `>`, `>=`, `<`, `<=` and ranges. Supported casts include `string`, `objectId`, `integer`, `float`, `boolean` and `date`.

`autoApplyFilter` defaults to `begin`; `autoApplySearch` is opt-in. Both can apply generated `$match` stages before or after the table aggregation.

## Hooks And Options

Important extension points:

- `onInit(req, out)` changes init payloads.
- `onRow(row)` transforms entries.
- `onAttributes(row)` adds `__cellattr`.
- `onData(req, data)` changes final data payload.
- `selectableFunctions` defines frontend-triggered bulk actions.
- `exports` defines downloadable export variants.
- `defaultUnwind` prepends an `$unwind` stage.
- `disablePerPageConfig` forces the class-defined `perPage`.

## DataBuilder

`DataBuilder` is a schema-driven CRUD layer for structured backend admin flows. It registers types, exposes frontend metadata, validates submitted data, maps fields into MongoDB documents and runs lifecycle hooks.

## Define A Type

```ts
import { DataBuilder } from "@webtypen/webframez-core";

const builder = new DataBuilder();

builder.registerType({
  key: "user",
  singular: "User",
  plural: "Users",
  schema: {
    version: "1.0.0",
    collection: "users",
    fields: {
      email: { type: "text", required: true, unique: { match: {} } },
      age: { type: "integer" }
    }
  }
});
```

You can also use `registerModelType(...)` for model-provided schemas and `registerFieldType(...)` for custom save/search behavior.

## Expose REST API

```ts
class MyDataBuilderController extends DataBuilderController {
  constructor() {
    super(builder);
  }
}

Route.post("/api/builder", "MyDataBuilderController@restApi");
```

Supported `__builder_rest_api` actions:

- `type`: return type/schema/forms metadata.
- `details`: load an existing item.
- `details-newdata`: call `newDataHandler`.
- `save`: validate and insert/update data.
- `delete`: delete an item if allowed.
- `api-autocomplete`: run a custom autocomplete field type search.

## Schema Hooks

Schemas may define `beforeSave`, `afterSave`, `beforeDelete`, `afterDelete`, `getAggregation`, `newDataHandler` and `canDelete`.

`fields` can be an object or function. Nested object and array schemas are supported. Built-in value mapping covers `ObjectId`, `currency`, `float`, `integer` and `datetime`.

## Validation

Required fields can be boolean or function-based. Unique checks can be custom functions or object definitions with optional `match`, `collection` and aggregation settings.

## Unmapped Types

If a type is marked `unmapped`, DataBuilder skips database persistence and delegates behavior to hooks. This is useful for virtual forms or backend actions that should still reuse the same frontend form infrastructure.

## Console Runtime

`ConsoleApplication` registers config, error handlers, datatables and jobs, then resolves a command from CLI arguments. It provides built-in system commands and also reads custom commands from `kernel.commands`.

```ts
import { BaseKernelConsole, ConsoleApplication, ConsoleCommand } from "@webtypen/webframez-core";

class HelloCommand extends ConsoleCommand {
  static signature = "hello";
  static description = "Print a greeting";

  async handle() {
    this.success("Hello world");
  }
}

class KernelConsole extends BaseKernelConsole {
  static commands = [HelloCommand];
}

new ConsoleApplication().boot({
  kernel: KernelConsole,
  config: {}
});
```

## Command Helpers

`ConsoleCommand` provides `getArguments()`, `getOptions()`, `getOption(name)`, `ask(question)`, `write`, `writeln`, `info`, `warning`, `success`, `error`, `progress(count)`, `progressIncrement()` and `progressFinish()`.

CLI options are parsed from `--key value`, `--key=value`, `-k value` and boolean flags.

## Queue Jobs

Queue jobs extend `BaseQueueJob` and implement `handle(job)`:

```ts
import { BaseQueueJob } from "@webtypen/webframez-core";

export class SendMailJob extends BaseQueueJob {
  async handle(job: any) {
    this.log("Sending mail", job.payload);
  }
}
```

Create entries with:

```ts
await SendMailJob.create({
  payload: { userId: "..." },
  priority: 5,
  worker: null
});
```

`BaseQueueJob` assigns an incrementing `number`, sets `jobclass`, `status = "pending"`, `created_at`, logs through `log(...)`, supports `wait(ms)` and can request delayed re-execution with `executeAgain(value, unit)`.

## Register Jobs

```ts
app.boot({
  jobs: [SendMailJob]
});
```

## Queue Config

Queue workers are configured under `config.queue.workers`:

```ts
export default {
  workers: {
    default: {
      is_active: true,
      jobclasses: ["SendMailJob"],
      automation: [
        {
          jobclass: "SendMailJob",
          executions: [
            ["every_x_mins", 15],
            ["daily", "08:00"],
            ["every_hour", 5],
            ["mondays", "09:30"]
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  }
};
```

